docs.abstract: President Trump’s scolding of prominent black athletes has touched off a furious national debate on race and patriotism, rattling the world of sports.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s scolding of prominent black athletes has touched off a furious national debate on race and patriotism, rattling the world of sports.
docs.lead_paragraph: It began as a crowd-pleasing tirade from President Trump to an overwhelmingly white, conservative crowd in Alabama. But even before dozens of N.F.L. players knelt in silent protest on Sunday, Mr. Trump’s remarks had spiraled into a national uproar over race, patriotism and free speech, with an unpredictable political trajectory.

headline.main: Defying Trump, Athletes Intensify Debate on Race and Protest
headline.print_headline: Simmering Debate on Race Reaches Boil  As More Athletes Join Chorus of Dissent

docs.abstract: The president’s inflammatory comments might not be as significant as the players’ responses.

headline.print_headline: The Provocateur President  Meets Athletes’ Resolve

docs.abstract: In a letter to Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg, Representative Robin Kelly demanded that he take seriously Russian efforts to exploit racial division.
docs.snippet: In a letter to Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg, Representative Robin Kelly demanded that he take seriously Russian efforts to exploit racial division.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Members of the Congressional Black Caucus pressured Facebook this week to seriously examine how the site allowed Russian operatives to use advertising to target Black Lives Matter and sow racial divisions ahead of last year’s election.

headline.main: Black Lawmakers Pressure Facebook Over Racially Divisive Russian Ads

docs.abstract: Trinity School’s headmaster sends shock waves through the city’s private-school world calling out insidious parental entitlement and self-interest.
docs.snippet: Trinity School’s headmaster sends shock waves through the city’s private-school world calling out insidious parental entitlement and self-interest.
docs.lead_paragraph: Earlier this month Princeton University Press published a book called “Uneasy Street: The Anxieties of Affluence,” by a sociologist, Rachel Sherman, who researched the spending habits of 50 well-to-do parents in New York City, and diagnosed a pervasive problem of reticence around wealth. Ms. Sherman uses her encounters with people who agreed to speak with her, in many cases about their fears of seeming showy, to conclude that there is too much silence around money and that all of this alleged hush and professed shame ultimately slow our efforts to mitigate inequality.

headline.main: Can Prep Schools Fight the Class War?

docs.abstract: LeBron James weighed in again, as he did on Saturday, when he referred to Trump as a “bum.” Toronto’s DeMar DeRozan compared Trump to a “12-year-old.”

docs.abstract: We all have many identities, and we do best when we’re able to move through them gracefully.
docs.snippet: We all have many identities, and we do best when we’re able to move through them gracefully.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Lebanese-born writer Amin Maalouf made an interesting point about identity: Other people often pick ours for us. The anti-Semite elevates the Jewish consciousness in the Jew. The Sunni radical elevates Shiite consciousness in the Shiite.

docs.abstract: The former presidential candidate and the politically active actress discuss the hurt of the 2016 election and how they are both moving on.
docs.snippet: The former presidential candidate and the politically active actress discuss the hurt of the 2016 election and how they are both moving on.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hiking, yoga, reading, prayer, chardonnay (but not Xanax): These are the things, along with family and friends, that helped Hillary Clinton after her stunning defeat in the presidential election last year. But these are gentle pastimes. What about kicking things — or weeping?

headline.main: Hillary Clinton and America Ferrera on Pain and Progress (and Hiking)

docs.abstract: James B. Comey, the former F.B.I. director, exhorted his audience to “listen with an attitude that they might actually be convinced of something.”
docs.snippet: James B. Comey, the former F.B.I. director, exhorted his audience to “listen with an attitude that they might actually be convinced of something.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — James. B. Comey, the former F.B.I. director, was met with raised fists and chants of “no justice, no peace” by protesters on Friday as he delivered the keynote address at Howard University’s convocation, marking a rocky re-emergence into public life since he was fired by President Trump in May.

headline.main: James Comey Is Interrupted by Protesters During Speech at Howard
